ts. Each of the chapters in this volume focuses on the reception of a particular individual or group, and together they will appeal to not only historians of religion, but those concerned with material culture, the cult of history, and with the reshaping of British identities in an age of faith and doubt.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aChristian saintsxCongressesxCultxHistoryx19th centuryxEngland. 0aChristian saintsxCultzEnglandxHistoryy19th centuryxCongresses. 0aSaintsxHistoryx19th centuryxGreat Britain. 0aSaintszGreat BritainxHistoryy19th century. 7aRELIGION / Christianity / History.2bisacsh  aCatholic.  aDoubt.  aFaith.  aHeroes.  aIdentity.  aNineteenth-Century Britain.  aProtestant.  aSaints.  aSanctity.  aVictorian.1 aAllpress, Roshan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAtkins, Gareth, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAtkins, Gareth, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aBurton, Simon, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aColeman, James, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHarris, Alana, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHerringer, Carol Engelhardt, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHolmes, Andrew R., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLedger-Lomas, Michael, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMacfarlane, Elizabeth, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRogers, Helen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSheils, William, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aUnderwood, Lucy, econtributor.4ctb